@node "installation" "Installing Heddley"
Installing Heddley could not be easier! Simply double-click on the
Install-Heddley icon to install Heddley and documentation to your system. You
must have the Commodore-Amiga Installer utility for installation to complete
successfully.

If you do not have the Installer utility, then you can download it from
Aminet, or find it in various places (such as on some old coverdisks etc).

If you don't want to do that, Heddley can be installed by copying the
following files (HEDD: indicates the pathname here where you want to install
Heddley - you don't have to make this assign!):

 Heddley/Archive/Heddley         to  HEDD:Heddley
 Heddley/Archive/Heddley.info    to  HEDD:Heddley.info
 Heddley/Archive/Heddley.guide   to  HEDD:Heddley.guide
 Heddley/Archive/edd.gif         to  HEDD:edd.gif
 Heddley/Archive/#?.rexx         to  REXX:
 Heddley/Archive/def_guide.info  to  ENVARC:sys/def_guide.info
 Heddley/Archive/def_guide.info  to  HEDD:Heddley.guide.info

(if you don't want to use MagicWB icons substitute def_guide_old.info for
def_guide.info and Heddley_old_unsnap.info for Heddley.info).
@endnode

@node "edit_guide" "Editing the database"
When you first start Heddley, you will be presented with the front panel. If
you have AmigaDos 3.0+, @{"click here" link "pictures/frontpanel.ilbm/main" 0} to see a picture of the window.

Function of the window gadgets:

    @{"Load" link "loadgadg" 0}
    @{"Save" link "savegadg" 0}
    @{"New" link "newgadg" 0}
    @{"Info" link "indexgadg" 0}

    @{"Database documents" link "docnamelist" 0}

    @{"Edit" link "edit_document" 0}
    @{"Add" link "adddocument" 0}
    @{"Attrib" link "attrib" 0}
    @{"Delete" link "delete" 0}
    @{"Up" link "movedocup" 0}
    @{"Dn" link "movedocdown" 0}

There is also a menu-strip:

    @{b}Project@{ub}

    About...
    -------------
    @{"Prefs..." link "prefswin" 0}
    @{"Save as HTML" link "html" 0}
    @{"Save as ANSI" link "ansi" 0}
    @{"Save as ASCII" link "save_ascii" 0}
    @{"Test Database" link "menu_testguide" 0}
    -------------
    Quit

To start editing a database, select either @{"Load" link "loadgadg" 0} or @{"New" link "newgadg" 0}. As an example, make a
copy of this document, and then load that into Heddley. Heddley will ONLY
display files with a suffix of .guide in its load and save file requesters.
Thus you should always name your AmigaGuide؟ databases with a .guide suffix.

To load a database, in addition to using the @{"Load" link "loadgadg" 0} gadget, you can drag and
drop a Workbench icon into the window.

When a database is loaded, or created, the list of documents within that
database appears in the Document name listview. These documents correspond to
the documents you will see on each page, when read with AmigaGuide؟ or
Multiview. The name of each document MUST BE unique. The reader does not see
this name, so it does not have to be that meaningful. The reader will,
however, see the document's title (which can be changed with the @{"Attrib" link "attrib" 0}
option).

You can alter each document by selecting it in the listview and then using
@{"Edit" link "edit_document" 0}, @{"Add" link "adddocument" 0}, @{"Attrib" link "attrib" 0} or @{"Delete" link "delete" 0}. Double clicking on an item is a shortcut for the
@{"Edit" link "edit_document" 0} option. Keyboard shortcuts are available as denoted by the underscored
letter in each gadget. The Esc key will quit Heddley (throughout Heddley
pressing Esc has the effect of closing the current window and, where
appropriate, selecting the 'Cancel' action).

When you have done editing your database, be sure to save it again. The text
will be justified to the width specified by the @{"TEXTWIDTH tooltype" link "tt_textwidth" 0} (whose
default is 78 characters).
@endnode

@node "edit_document" "Editing a document"
The edit window provides the main interface for editing a document. The window
shows the current text, with buttons highlighted. A scroller is available to
move up and down the text (you can also use cursor keys for this too).

If you have AmigaDos 3.0+, @{"click here" link "pictures/doceditwin.ilbm/main" 0} for a picture of this window.

Control is by means of menus. The following menu items are available:

        @{b}Document@{ub}        @{b}Buttons@{ub}                 @{b}Preferences@{ub}

        @{"Edit attributes" link "attrib" 0} @{"Apply style to text" link "textstyle" 0}     @{"Smooth scroll" link "menu_smoothscroll" 0}
        @{"Clear text" link "menu_cleartext" 0}      @{"Make into button" link "menu_makebutton" 0}
        @{"Load new text" link "menu_loadtext" 0}   @{"Delete button" link "menu_delbutton" 0}
        @{"Edit text" link "menu_edittext" 0}       @{"Replicate button" link "menu_replicate" 0}
        --------------
        Exit

Text can be inserted by means of the options in the Document menu. You can
also replace the text in the window with that of your choice by dragging an
icon in from the Workbench (obviously it helps if it is the icon of a text
file!!!)

You can highlight portions of the text by drag-clicking with the mouse. Once a
portion of text is highlighted, you can turn it into a button (using the Make
into button menu option), or you can apply a text style (using the Apply
style... menu option), such as @{b}bold@{ub} or @{i}italic@{ui}, or change the text @{fg shine}coloring@{fg text}.
You can highlight a word at a time by double clicking on a word and then
dragging the mouse whilst holding the button down on the second click.

To edit an existing button, just click on it, and the @{"Button Edit window" link "butteditwin" 0} will
opened.

When you have finished editing the document, either press Esc or use the Exit
menu option to return to the front panel.
@endnode

@node "other" "Other Information"
@{u}AmigaGuide؟@{uu}

For more information about what AmigaGuide؟ is, and is about:

    1.  have a good play with it.
    2.  read my article on p.108 of the July '94 edition
        of Amiga User International.
    3.  obtain the AmigaGuide؟ developers' distribution (from Aminet,
        for instance) and read the documentation.
@endnode

@node "adddocument" "The Add document gadget"
Selecting the Add gadget adds a new document into the database. Initially the
document has a stupid name, which you will do well to change into something
more meaningful for yourself. The new document is merely a "blank", but by use
of the @{"Attrib" link "attrib" 0} and @{"Edit" link "edit_document" 0} gadgets you can edit the title and text of this
document.

New documents are always added at the end of the document list; the order of
the documents is only used for the 'Save as ANSI' feature, where the documents
are output in the order they are shown in the listview.
@endnode

@node "attrib" "The Attrib gadget"
Selecting the Attrib gadget opens the Document Attribute window. If you have
AmigaDos 3.0+ @{"click here" link "pictures/attribwin.ilbm/main" 0} for a picture of this window.

Function of the window gadgets:

    @{b}Doc. ID@{ub} :   this option controls the name of the document as seen
                in the listview gadget of the front panel. Note that
                this @{i}MUST BE UNIQUE@{ui} for AmigaGuide؟ to recognise your
                document. You cannot change the name of the MAIN
                document as every database needs a MAIN document as a
                starting point.

    @{b}Title@{ub}   :   This gadget shows the title which will appear in the
                title bar when you are viewing this document. Alter
                this so it reflects the contents of your document.

    @{b}TOC@{ub}     :   Every document can have an individual contents document,
                if it is desired. The default contents page is MAIN
                but you can use this gadget to change it if you want.
                Note that a contents page is specific to a particular
                document.

    @{b}Next@{ub}    :   When using the "Browse" buttons in AmigaGuide, you can
                specify which document follows the current one. Select
                the name of the document to follow, or ،noneﭨ for the
                default successor (as in the listview).

    @{b}Prev@{ub}    :   When using the "Browse" buttons in AmigaGuide, you can
                specify which document is moved to using the "Browse <"
                button. Select the name of the document to follow, or
                ،noneﭨ for the default predecessor (as in the listview).

Use Esc, 'Cancel' or the close gadget to close this window and cancel any
changes you have made, or 'Okay' to keep them.
@endnode

@node "delete" "The Delete gadget"
Selecting this gadget will remove @{i}FOR EVER@{ui} the current document (as displayed
at the base of the listview) from the database. USE WITH CARE!
@endnode

@node "menu_cleartext" "Clear text"
Selecting this option will wipe all the text and buttons in the current
document, leaving you with a blank document.
@endnode

@node "menu_loadtext" "Load text"
Selecting Load text will enable you to load a new text file into the document
window. All current text and buttons will be cleared. Buttons can then be
added into the text to produce your document.
@endnode

@node "menu_edittext" "Edit text"
This option allows you to edit the actual text of the document.

Heddley compiles the current document into AmigaGuide؟ format, and invokes
your text editor with the compiled text as its argument. The default editor is
"ed", but you can change this by setting the EDITOR environmental variable, or
altering the @{"EDITOR tooltype" link "tt_editor" 0}, before you start up Heddley. Heddley starts the
text editor by performing the command:

    <editorname> <temporaryfile>

The contents of the current document are placed in the temporary file, which
you must save back before you quit the editor. Do NOT change the name of this
file.

Also, your text editor must run SYNCHRONOUSLY. This is because Heddley waits
until the editor has finished and then reloads the document. If your editor
spawns another process then Heddley will immediately reload the document and
not wait; obviously not very desirable. If you use an asynchronous text
editor, you need to write some @{"ARexx scripts" link "rexx_examples" 0} to coordinate your editor with
Heddley.

You will notice that buttons are translated into their AmigaGuide؟ form in
this text, this is in order to preserve them during the edit. Unless you are
sure of yourself, don't touch these definitions (these are the bits of text
with a \@{ at the beginning and a } at the end}.

When you finish editing, select the save-and-quit option from your text
editor. Heddley will then redisplay your edited text. Note that this may take
a small while for big files; Heddley's retranslating mechanism is a little
slow at the moment, but it enables Heddley to do 'the right thing' by spaces.
@endnode

@node "menu_makebutton" "Make into button"
Selecting this option allows you to create a button in your document. To use
it you must have some text highlighted (use the mouse to do this). Heddley
will then create a button and open the @{"Button Edit window" link "butteditwin" 0}.

Normally, AmigaGuide does NOT allow multi-line buttons. However, if you select
more than one line in Heddley and turn it into a button, Heddley will
translate this into a button for each line. When you reload the database (or
edit the document), each line will have its separate button. But for the first
time (ie. just after you created the multi-line button) all the line-buttons
will be amalgamated into one button. There should be no visible difference!
@endnode

@node "menu_delbutton" "Delete button"
This option allows you to remove a button. Simply select this option, and then
click on the button you wish to remove. If you decide not to remove a button
after all, reselect the Delete button menu-option to cancel the operation.
@endnode

@node "butteditwin" "The Button Edit window"
The Button Edit window allows you to alter the nature of the button you are
editing. If you have AmigaDos 3.0+, @{"click here" link "pictures/butteditwin.ilbm/main" 0} to see a picture of the
window.

Function of the window gadgets:

    @{b}Button type@{ub} -   the button type determines what will happen when the
                    reader clicks on this button. See Button Types for
                    more information.

    @{b}Command@{ub}     -   this is the name of the AmigaDOS/ARexx command
                    (or ARexx script) that will be executed when
                    the reader clicks on this button. Only applicable
                    if button type is one of AmigaDOS command,
                    ARexx command, or ARexx script.

    @{b}Document@{ub}    -   this is the name of the document which the current
                    button will take the reader to, when clicked. If it
                    is an internal link (see Button Types) then it will
                    be the name of another document in the current
                    database.
                    If it is an external link then it can be any text file
                    or AmigaGuide؟ file (WB2) or any Workbench 3 datatype
                    supported file.

    @{b}Line #@{ub}      -   this is the top line of the document that will be
                    displayed with a document/text file link.

    @{b}New wnd@{ub}     -   if this gadget is checked, then the link will cause
                    the linked document to load in a NEW WINDOW of
                    AmigaGuide. Try this and see!

    @{b}Choose Doc@{ub}  -   Click on the Choose Doc button to bring a list of
                    documents (internal link) or a file requester (external
                    link) to choose the link document from.

    @{b}Create Doc@{ub}  -   Click on this button to create a new document there
                    and then. This is useful as you often think of the need
                    for a new document whilst writing an existing one.
                    Clicking here will add a new document and open the
                    @{"Attrib Window" link "attrib" 0} for the newly created document.

Use Esc, 'Cancel' or the close gadget to cancel your alterations, or 'Okay' to
keep them.
@endnode

@node "loadgadg" "Load database"
Use of this gadget will open a file requester to load a new database. The
database must have a .guide suffix.

In the case of malformed AmigaGuide databases (ie. those with various syntax
errors and so on) Heddley will try and do its best, although there is a
possibility that very malformed files will crash Heddley.

If the database has no name then it will be given the name "Unnamed_Database".
Documents with no name get given one, documents with no title get a copy of
the name as a title. If the database you load does not have a "Main" node,
Heddley will add one for you. Links with no destination become links to
"Heddley_Error".

However, Heddley can be temperamental and if you do find a .guide which causes
Heddley to either crash or make Enforcer hits, please please please mail @{"me" link "author" 0}
with a copy of the .guide that caused the problem and a description of the
problem.
@endnode

@node "savegadg" "Save"
This gadget will open a file requester in order for you to choose the file to
save the database to. Be sure to give your file a .guide suffix.
@endnode

@node "indexgadg" "The Info Window"
The Info window allows you set various database-wide attributes: Index, Help
document, Author, Version, Copyright notice, wordwrap and database font. If
you have AmigaDos 3.0+, @{"click here" link "pictures/infowindow.ilbm/main" 0} to see a picture of this window.

@{u}Index@{uu}

The @{b}Index@{ub} gadget will allow you to set the index document for the current
database. The Index node will be displayed when the reader clicks the Index
gadget in AmigaGuide؟ or Multiview.                         

Select ، none ﭨ to disable the index (this is the default).

Select ، auto ﭨ to make Heddley create the index automatically for you. For an
example of this, see the @{"index" alink "HeddleyAutoIndex" 0} to this database (press the Index gadget or
select Index from the @{"Contents" link "Main" 0} page). Heddley creates an alphabetical list of
document titles, followed by an alphabetical list of all links within document
(this includes ARexx commands etc., although I may change this later if I
change my mind...)

The index document is given the name HeddleyAutoIndex, so avoid using this
name for your own documents, and if you want to create extra links to the
index, enter HeddleyAutoIndex in the internal link @{"document name gadget" link "butteditwin" 0} for a
button.

@{u}Help@{uu}

The @{b}Help@{ub} gadget will allow you to set the help document that is displayed when
the user presses HELP in AmigaGuide/MultiView or selects the Help gadget.
Either select a document in your database, or ، default ﭨ to use the
@{"normal AmigaGuide help file" alink "help" 0}, which is normally stored in "s:help.guide".

@{u}Author@{uu}

The @{b}Author@{ub} gadget allows you to edit the recorded author of the database. For
a new database, the default value of this field is the contents of the AUTHOR
environmental variable.

@{u}(C)@{uu}

The @{b}(C)@{ub} gadget allows you to edit the copyright message of the database. For a
new database, the default value of this is the contents of the COMPANY
environmental variable.

@{u}Version@{uu}

The @{b}Version@{ub} gadget allows you to keep version control on your database. On
creation of a new database, this field is set to '1.0'. The version of a
database created this way can be found by using the C:Version command:

    version mydatabase.guide                

@{u}Wrap@{uu}

The @{b}Wrap@{ub} gadget allows you to use the @{"AmigaGuide V39" link "ag39" 0} wordwrap facility. This
lets AmigaGuide do the formatting, instead of Heddley. When this option is
used, you can also choose the font for your database with the Font gadget. I
advise against using this in documents which are meant to be read in anything
but AmigaGuide V39+ as it makes documents virtually unreadable for Workbench
2.x users.

Of course, if you are a Workbench 2.x user and come across someone else's
database written this way, you can easily use Heddley to convert it to a more
readable form! Ain't life sweet?
@endnode

@node "newgadg" "Starting a new database"
Selecting this gadget will wipe all the current database, and start a new
database. The MAIN node will be automatically created for you.
@endnode

@node "docnamelist" "The document name list"
This list shows the unique IDs of each document in the database. Use the
scroller to move up and down this list. Double-clicking on an entry will open
the @{"edit window" link "edit_document" 0} for that document.
@endnode

@node "startingup" "Starting Heddley"
Heddley can be run from either the Workbench, or the command line. From
Workbench:

    Double-click on Heddley's icon. If you have shift-clicked a guide
    file beforehand, that file will be loaded into Heddley on startup.

From the Shell:

    Change to the directory where Heddley is stored, and type
    "Heddley". Heddley accepts command line arguments, similar to
    the @{"tooltypes" link "configuring" 0} available in the icon, but parsed according to the
    following template:

    FILE,@{"FONT" link "tt_font" 0}/K,@{"FONTSIZE" link "tt_fontsize" 0}/K/N,@{"TEXTWIDTH" link "tt_textwidth" 0}/K/N,@{"EDITOR" link "tt_editor" 0}/K,
        @{"FGPEN" link "tt_fgpen" 0}/K/N,@{"BGPEN" link "tt_bgpen" 0}/K/N,@{"HELPFILE" link "tt_helpfile" 0}/K

    For example:

    heddley FONT Courier.font FONTSIZE 13 EDITOR "vi" myguide.guide

    ...will start up Heddley using 13pt Courier, "vi" as the default
    editor and automatically load in "myguide.guide" for editing.
@endnode

@node "configuring" "Configuring Heddley"
Heddley can be configured in three ways:

    * the @{"'Prefs...'" link "prefswin" 0} option from the main menu
    * the @{"ARexx port" link "arexx" 0}
    * the tooltypes of Heddley's icon

Heddley processes the configuration in the following order:

    @{"'Prefs...'" link "prefswin" 0} settings _override_ tooltypes

Heddley's configuration can be stored in the tooltypes of Heddley's icon. To
view these, select Heddley's icon and select 'Information' from the 'Icons'
menu of Workbench. Here is a list of the tooltypes:

    @{"FONT" link "tt_font" 0}
    @{"FONTSIZE" link "tt_fontsize" 0}
    @{"TEXTWIDTH" link "tt_textwidth" 0}
    @{"EDITOR" link "tt_editor" 0}
    @{"FGPEN" link "tt_fgpen" 0}
    @{"BGPEN" link "tt_bgpen" 0}
    @{"HELPFILE" link "tt_helpfile" 0}

If you start Heddley from the @{"Shell" link "startingup" 0}, these tooltypes can be used as parameters
for Heddley.

The values of these tooltypes can be found using the @{"ARexx" link "arexx" 0} @{"QUERY" link "r_query" 0} command when
Heddley is running.
@endnode

@node "arexx" "The ARexx port"
Heddley's ARexx port offers all the functionality of the front GUI panel, and
more besides. The portname is HEDDLEY.N, where N is the instance of Heddley
you wish to control. This will usually be 1.

Here is a list of all the commands that Heddley supports:

    @{" ADD     " link "r_add" 0}
    @{" ATTRIB  " link "r_attrib" 0}
    @{" DELETE  " link "r_delete" 0}
    @{" EDIT    " link "r_edit" 0}
    @{" GOTO    " link "r_goto" 0}
    @{" INFO    " link "r_info" 0}    * changed from INDEX since v1.0
    @{" LOAD    " link "r_load" 0}
    @{" LOCK    " link "r_lock" 0}
    @{" MOVE    " link "r_move" 0}
    @{" NEW     " link "r_new" 0}
    @{" PENS    " link "r_pems" 0}
    @{" PREFS   " link "r_prefs" 0}    * new for v1.1
    @{" QUERY   " link "r_query" 0}    * new variables for v1.1
    @{" QUIT    " link "r_quit" 0}
    @{" SAVE    " link "r_save" 0}
    @{" TEST    " link "r_test" 0}    * new for v1.1

Using the ARexx port will allow you to interface Heddley with an asynchronous
text editor; see the @{"examples" link "rexx_examples" 0} for more information.

The on-line help facility also offers an @{"AmigaGuide AREXX port" link "ag_arexx" 0}.
@endnode

@node "tt_font" "The FONT tooltype"
This tooltype selects the font for the @{"document edit window" link "edit_document" 0}. It must be a
fixed-width font. Default:

    FONT=topaz.font

Don't forget the .font suffix!

If your font cannot be found, or if it is proportionally spaced, then the
default will be used.
@endnode

@node "tt_fontsize" "The FONTSIZE tooltype"
FONTSIZE

This tooltype selects the font size for the document edit window. Default:

    FONTSIZE=8

If the needed size does not exist, then the nearest size available will be
scaled up/down as needed.
@endnode

@node "tt_editor" "The EDITOR tooltype"
This tooltype selects the text editor to be used when @{"editing a document's" link "menu_edittext" 0}
@{"contents" link "menu_edittext" 0}. Default:

    EDITOR=ed

The text editor must run synchronously (not spawn its own process). If you use
GoldEd, the recommended setting is:

    EDITOR=ed sticky

Where the 'ed' is the GoldEd quick-start editor.

If the EDITOR tooltype is NOT specified, then if the EDITOR environmental
variable is set, it this will be used instead.
@endnode

@node "tt_textwidth" "The TEXTWIDTH tooltype"
This tooltype selects the normal width of text justification, both for the
edit window and outputted documents. The default is:

    TEXTWIDTH=78

If the font or text width you choose makes the text too wide to display in the
window, the largest possible width will be used for the window display.

TEXTWIDTH has a minimum value of 1; and using a value of 1 is not a good idea
as there may be some bugs in Heddley's output routines at the moment which
lead to strange output source. You have been warned!

It is not recommended that you change TEXTWIDTH from 78, as this is the most
number of columns that can be displayed on a normal screen with topaz-8 as the
font.

It is ALWAYS better to justify to 78 characters, for the benefit of Workbench
2 users. Be nice!
@endnode

@node "tt_helpfile" "The HELPFILE tooltype"
This tooltype enables you to specify where Heddley should look for its
documentation file for the @{"on-line help" link "helpfunc" 0} facility. For example, if you like to
keep all your documentation in a partition called 'MAN:' you might specify:

    HELPFILE=MAN:Heddley.guide

The default is:

    HELPFILE=Heddley.guide

This means Heddley will look for the file Heddley.guide in the directory that
it was started from.
@endnode

@node "tt_fgpen" "The FGPEN tooltype"
FGPEN controls the logical number of the pen used to render the text in the
document edit window. The default is:

    FGPEN=1                                
@endnode

@node "tt_bgpen" "The BGPEN tooltype"
BGPEN controls the logical number of the pen used to render the background in
the document edit window. The default is:

    BGPEN=0                                
@endnode

@node "r_add" "ADD"
COMMAND

    @{b}ADD@{ub}

SYNTAX

    ADD NAME/K,NEW/S

DESCRIPTION

    Adds a new document into the document list.
    If a @{b}NAME@{ub} is specified, that name is used for the new document,
    otherwise if @{b}NEW@{ub} is specified, a unique name is automatically
    generated.                                 
@endnode

@node "r_attrib" "ATTRIB"
COMMAND

    @{b}ATTRIB@{ub}

SYNTAX

    ATTRIB NAME/K,TITLE/K,TOC/K,GUI/S,NEXT/K,PREV/K

DESCRIPTION

    ATTRIB changes the attributes of the current document. If @{b}NAME, TITLE
    TOC, NEXT@{ub} or @{b}PREV@{ub} are specified then the relevant attributes are
    updated:

        @{b}NAME@{ub}    ASCII unique document name
        @{b}TITLE@{ub}   ASCII title of document
        @{b}TOC@{ub}     ASCII document name for document table of contents
        @{b}NEXT@{ub}    ASCII document name of Browse > successor
        @{b}PREV@{ub}    ASCII document name of Browse < predecessor

    If @{b}GUI@{ub} is specified then Heddley will open the @{"Edit Attribute" link "attrib" 0} window
    and let the user change the attributes.                                 
@endnode

@node "r_delete" "DELETE"
COMMAND

    @{b}DELETE@{ub}

SYNTAX

    DELETE NAME/K,NUMBER/K/N,CURRENT/S

DESCRIPTION

    DELETE deletes a document from the document list.

    @{b}CURRENT@{ub} deletes the current document.
    @{b}NAME@{ub}    deletes the document with specified name.
    @{b}NUMBER@{ub}  deletes the document specified by position in the list.
@endnode

@node "r_edit" "EDIT"
COMMAND

    @{b}EDIT@{ub}

SYNTAX

    EDIT LOADTEXT/K,PLAIN/S,GUI/S,SAVETEXT/K

DESCRIPTION

    EDIT allows editing of the current document text. If @{b}GUI@{ub} is specified,
    the @{"document edit window" link "edit_document" 0} is opened and an interactive editing session
    started.

    @{b}LOADTEXT@{ub} and @{b}SAVETEXT@{ub} allow the contents of the document to be loaded
    from and saved to a file. In @{b}LOADTEXT@{ub}, the file contents will be
    interpreted as an AmigaGuide؟ file, and in @{b}SAVETEXT@{ub} AmigaGuide؟ control
    information will be saved in the text. This feature is useful for
    interfacing Heddley with asynchronous editors. If you just want the
    plain text to be loaded/saved and buttons ignored, specify the @{b}PLAIN@{ub}
    switch. 
@endnode

@node "r_goto" "GOTO"
COMMAND

    @{b}GOTO@{ub}

SYNTAX

    GOTO NAME/K,NUMBER/N/K

DESCRIPTION

    GOTO selects a document to be the current document in Heddley.
    If @{b}NAME@{ub} is specified then the node of that name is activated. Note that
    the search is case insensitive. If @{b}NUMBER@{ub} is specified, then the
    document with the specified position in the listview is made the
    current one.
@endnode

@node "r_info" "INFO"
COMMAND

    @{b}INFO@{ub}

SYNTAX

    INFO INDEX/K,HELP/K,AUTHOR/K,COPYRIGHT/K,VERSION/K,NOHELP/S,
    AUTOINDEX/S,NOINDEX/S,GUI/S

DESCRIPTION

    The INFO command is used to alter global attributes of the database.

    Indexing:

    @{b}INDEX@{ub}       sets the index document name.
    @{b}NOINDEX@{ub}     specifies no index is to be used for this database.
    @{b}AUTOINDEX@{ub}   enables @{"automatic index creation" link "indexgadg" 0} for this database.

    Help:

    @{b}HELP@{ub}        sets the help document name.
    @{b}NOHELP@{ub}      specifies AmigaGuide default help to be used.

    Version control:

    @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}      sets the database's author.
    @{b}COPYRIGHT@{ub}   sets the copyright notice of the database.
    @{b}VERSION@{ub}     sets the version string of the database.

    Other:

    @{b}GUI@{ub}         opens the @{"info window" link "indexgadg" 0} to allow the user to choose and
                see the attributes.

NOTE

    This command @{i}supersedes@{ui} the INDEX command from version 1.0 of
    Heddley.
@endnode

@node "r_load" "LOAD"
COMMAND

    @{b}LOAD@{ub}

SYNTAX

    LOAD FILE,CONFIRM/S,REQUEST/S

DESCRIPTION

    LOAD loads a new database into Heddley's memory. @{b}CONFIRM@{ub} asks the user
    if they're sure they want to load a new database, if they have made
    changes to the current database. @{b}REQUEST@{ub} puts up a file requester on
    the screen to get the file to load from the user.
@endnode

@node "r_lock" "LOCK"
COMMAND

    @{b}LOCK@{ub}

SYNTAX

    LOCK UNLOCK/S

DESCRIPTION

    LOCK locks the front panel of Heddley so the user cannot use any
    of the gadgets. It also changes the pointer to a wait-pointer.
    Using the @{b}UNLOCK@{ub} argument unlocks the window.

    (Un)locking a window more than once has no ill-effects.

BUGS

    At the moment, LOCK does *not* prohibit AppWindow behaviour, so it
    is still possible to load a database using icon-dropping while the
    front panel is locked.
@endnode

@node "r_new" "NEW"
COMMAND

    @{b}NEW@{ub}

SYNTAX

    NEW CONFIRM/S

DESCRIPTION

    NEW wipes the current database and initialises Heddley with a new
    database. A new database consists of an empty Main document.
    Specifying @{b}CONFIRM@{ub} option will ask the user if they are sure they want
    to wipe the current database if it has been modified.
@endnode

@node "r_pems" "PENS"
COMMAND

    @{b}PENS@{ub}

SYNTAX

    PENS FGPEN/K/N,BGPEN/K/N

DESCRIPTION

    PENS allows the setting of the pens used to render the button edit
    window. The functions of the parameters @{"FGPEN" link "tt_fgpen" 0} and @{"BGPEN" link "tt_bgpen" 0} are
    as for their corresponding tooltypes.
@endnode

@node "r_query" "QUERY"
COMMAND

    @{b}QUERY@{ub}

SYNTAX

    QUERY ATTRIB/A,VAR/K/A

DESCRIPTION

    QUERY retrieves the value of an internal Heddley variable (attribute)
    and places it in the ARexx variable specified after the @{b}VAR@{ub} keyword.

    Example:

        QUERY FILENAME VAR THEFILE
        SAY 'Current filename is:' THEFILE

HEDDLEY ATTRIBUTES

    @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}          Author of the current database. Set using @{"INFO" link "r_info" 0} AUTHOR.

    @{b}BGPEN@{ub}           Pen used for background in button edit window.
                    See @{"BGPEN tooltype" link "tt_bgpen" 0}. Set using the @{"PENS" link "r_pems" 0} command.

    @{b}BUTTPEN@{ub}         Pen used for button highlight in button edit window.
                    See @{"BUTTPEN tooltype" link "tt_buttpen" 0}. Set using the @{"PENS" link "r_pems" 0} command.

    @{b}CHANGED@{ub}         TRUE if database has been changed since last load/save
                    operation, FALSE otherwise.

    @{b}COPYRIGHT@{ub}       The copyright notice of the current database. Set using
                    @{"INFO" link "r_info" 0} COPYRIGHT.

    @{b}CURRENT@{ub}         The name of the current document (as shown in the
                    listview in the front panel) or empty if there is none.
                    See @{"GOTO" link "r_goto" 0} and @{"ATTRIB" link "r_attrib" 0}.

    @{b}DATABASE@{ub}        The name of the current database.

    @{b}DBVERSION@{ub}       The version of the current database. Set using @{"INFO" link "r_info" 0}
                    VERSION.

    @{b}DIRNAME@{ub}         The name of the current directory of the current
                    database.

    @{b}DOCFILENAME@{ub}     The temporary filename of the current document text.
                    You should not normally need this.

    @{b}DOCNEXT@{ub}         The name of the browse-successor document, if set.
                    Set with @{"ATTRIB" link "r_attrib" 0}. See also the @{"Attrib window" link "attrib" 0}.

    @{b}DOCPREV@{ub}         The name of the browse-predecessor document if set.
                    Set with @{"ATTRIB" link "r_attrib" 0}. See also the @{"Attrib window" link "attrib" 0}.

    @{b}DOCTITLE@{ub}        The title of the current document. Set with @{"ATTRIB" link "r_attrib" 0}.

    @{b}DOCTOC@{ub}          The table of contents of the current document, or empty
                    if default toc. See @{"ATTRIB" link "r_attrib" 0}.

    @{b}EDITOR@{ub}          The text editor used for document editing. See the
                    @{"EDITOR tooltype" link "tt_editor" 0} and @{"Edit Text" link "menu_edittext" 0} in the button edit
                    window.

    @{b}FGPEN@{ub}           The pen used for rendering text in the document edit
                    window. See @{"FGPEN tooltype" link "tt_fgpen" 0}. Set using the @{"PENS" link "r_pems" 0} command.

    @{b}FILENAME@{ub}        The filename (relative to the current DIRNAME) of the
                    current database. Set according to the most recent load
                    or save operation.

    @{b}FONTNAME@{ub}        The name (.font extension compulsory) of the font used
                    in the button edit window. See the @{"FONT tooltype" link "tt_font" 0}.

    @{b}FONTSIZE@{ub}        The Y-size of the font in the button edit window.
                    See the @{"FONTSIZE tooltype" link "tt_fontsize" 0}.

    @{b}HELP@{ub}            The name of the help document in the current database.
                    Set using the @{"INFO" link "r_info" 0} HELP command.

    @{b}INDEX@{ub}           The name of the index document in the current database.
                    Set using the @{"INFO" link "r_info" 0} INDEX command.

    @{b}INFORMATION@{ub}     Full version string.

    @{b}ISMAIN@{ub}          TRUE if the current document is the Main document.

    @{b}LOADED@{ub}          TRUE if a database is being edited, FALSE if not.

    @{b}MASTER@{ub}          The *full* pathname of the database being edited (note
                    that relative pathnames are allowed; relative to the
                    directory Heddley was started from).

    @{b}TEXTWIDTH@{ub}       The width of the justification in the button edit
                    window.
                    Set using the @{"TEXTWIDTH tooltype" link "tt_textwidth" 0}.

    @{b}VERSION@{ub}         The version number of Heddley. Use this if you want to
                    write ARexx scripts which need a new version of
                    Heddley.
@endnode

@node "r_quit" "QUIT"
COMMAND

    @{b}QUIT@{ub}

SYNTAX

    QUIT CONFIRM/S

DESCRIPTION

    QUIT causes Heddley to quit. If @{b}CONFIRM@{ub} is specified, then the user is
    asked to confirm the quit action if they have not saved alterations
    to the current database.
@endnode

@node "r_save" "SAVE"
COMMAND

    @{b}SAVE@{ub}

SYNTAX

    SAVE FILE,REQUEST/S,NOICON/S,HTML/S,ANSI/S,STRIP/S

DESCRIPTION

    SAVE causes Heddley to save the current database. If the @{b}FILE@{ub} argument
    is specified then that argument overrides the current filename.
    If @{b}REQUEST@{ub} is specified then a file requester is opened and a filename
    obtained from the user.
    If @{b}NOICON@{ub} is specified the creation of an icon for the current
    database is suppressed. Heddley attempts to use
    
        ENVARC:sys/def_guide.info

    as the database icon, or else the default project icon. Note that if
    an icon already exists, it will never be overwritten, irrespective of
    whether @{b}NOICON@{ub} was specified.                     

    If @{b}HTML@{ub} is specified, then the database will be saved out as HTML,
    not AmigaGuide, source. See @{"Saving HTML source" link "html" 0}.  
    As Heddley saves directories for HTML source, the icon saved will
    be the default drawer icon.

    If @{b}ANSI@{ub} is specified then the database will be saved out as ASCII with
    ANSI standard control sequences for colors and text style. See
    @{"Saving ANSI source" link "ansi" 0}. The icon saved will be the default project icon.

    If @{b}ANSI@{ub} is in use and @{b}STRIP@{ub} is specified, then the ANSI color codes will
    be removed from the output, and just plain ASCII saved.
@endnode

@node "r_test" "TEST"
COMMAND

    @{b}TEST@{ub}

SYNTAX

    TEST

DESCRIPTION

    TEST causes Heddley to output the current database to a temporary file
    (of the format 'T:<unique-number>.tguide'). It then tells AmigaGuide to
    display that database.

    Database viewing is an asynchronous operation.

    See the menu item, @{"'Test Database'" link "menu_testguide" 0}.
@endnode

@node "r_prefs" "PREFS"
COMMAND

    @{b}PREFS@{ub}

SYNTAX

    PREFS   LOAD/S,SAVE/S,GUI/S

DESCRIPTION

    PREFS @{b}LOAD@{ub} loads the preferences from S:Heddley.prefs
    PREFS @{b}SAVE@{ub} saves the preferences into S:Heddley.prefs
    PREFS @{b}GUI@{ub} opens the @{"preferences window" link "prefswin" 0} and obtains preferences
    settings from the user.
@endnode

@node "r_move" "MOVE"
COMMAND

    @{b}MOVE@{ub}

SYNTAX

    MOVE    UP/S,DOWN/S

DESCRIPTION

    MOVE moves the current document one place up or down the document list,
    according to the specified arguments.
@endnode

@node "rexx_examples" "ARexx examples"
@{u}Example ARexx scripts@{uu}

Some ARexx scripts to work with Heddley and other applications have been
written. To view them, click on the relevant button below. (If the scripts do
not live in REXX: type ASSIGN REXX: <rexxdir> ADD at the CLI in order for the
below to work - where <rexxdir> is where the Heddley ARexx scripts are
stored).

    @{"editnode.rexx" link "REXX:editnode.rexx/main" 0}
    -   Grabbing a document from Heddley into GoldED

    @{"savenode.rexx" link "REXX:savenode.rexx/main" 0}
    -   Writing a document back from GoldED to Heddley

    @{"databaseinfo.rexx" link "REXX:databaseinfo.rexx/main" 0}
    -   Prints information about current Heddley database 
        @{"CLICK HERE" system "rx databaseinfo.rexx >CON://///CLOSE/WAIT"} to run this script (only works if you've got
        the scripts in REXX:)      

    @{"hedd_empty.rexx" link "REXX:hedd_empty.rexx/main" 0}
    -   An empty template for writing Heddley ARexx scripts in

    @{"hedd_golded_temp.rexx" link "REXX:hedd_golded_temp.rexx/main" 0}
    -   An empty template for writing GoldED - Heddley ARexx scripts in
@endnode

